              {
                "type": "output_text",
                "text": "Wikipedia presents Euler's identity as the equation\n\ne^{iπ} + 1 = 0\n\n(or equivalently e^{iπ} = −1), which links the five fundamental constants 0, 1, π, e and i and is often cited as an exemplar of mathematical beauty. It is a special case of Euler's formula\n\ne^{ix} = cos x + i sin x,\n\nobtained by setting x = π. Wikipedia gives a standard proof using the Taylor (power‑series) expansions of e^x, sin x and cos x: the series for e^{ix} groups into the cosine part plus i times the sine part, so e^{ix} = cos x + i sin x, and with cos π = −1 and sin π = 0 one gets e^{iπ} = −1 (hence e^{iπ}+1=0). Wikipedia also notes the historical attribution to Euler (published in Introductio in analysin infinitorum) and discusses the identity’s significance and reception as a beautiful, deep relation in mathematics.",
